s, channels, etc. | Neurons, filters, heads, channels, layers |\n| Hardware speedup | Depends on implementation | Usually better for real speedup |\n| Example question | “How important is this part?” | “Can we remove this whole channel/head/filter?” |\n\n---\n\n## Important point\n\nThese are not necessarily opposites.\n\nA method can be both:\n\n- **structured**, because it removes whole channels or heads, and\n- **importance-aware**, because it uses gradients, activations, or saliency to decide which ones to remove.\n\nFor example:\n\n```text\nUse an importance score to rank attention heads,\nthen prune the least important heads.\n```\n\nThat would be a type of **structured pruning** with an advanced pruning criterion.\n\n---\n\nSo the short answer is:\n\n> **Structured pruning is about removing entire components of a model. “Cogalent pruning,” if it is an importance-aware method, is about how those components are selected for removal.**  \n> They can overlap.",
