        "assistant": "Cogalent pruning differs from magnitude pruning in the criterion used to remove elements:\n\n- **Magnitude pruning** removes elements based on an **individual importance score**, usually the size or magnitude of a weight, activation, neuron, or parameter. Small-magnitude elements are assumed to contribute less and are pruned.\n\n- **Cogalent pruning** removes elements based on **joint redundancy across paired elements**. Instead of asking “Which element is least important by itself?”, it asks “Which two elements are co-redundant, and can we keep one while dropping the other?”\n\nSo the key distinction is:\n\n> **Magnitude pruning is importance-driven at the individual-element level; cogalent pruning is redundancy-driven at the paired-element level.**\n\nFor example, if two components perform nearly the same role, cogalent pruning may keep one and remove the other even if both individually appear important. Magnitude pruning, by contrast, would be more likely to remove whichever components have the smallest individual scores, regardless of pairwise redundancy.",
